{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_eagle_ver01/data/sn84024827/00211106633/1910092501/0164.xml":{"full_text":"m\nWS\n9?\ns?S?\n1\nit -jejik\n\nSECOND SECTION\n\n4\nDAILY REVIEW\n\nA. v\nPAGES 9 TO 12\n\nREGULAR MEMBER ASSOCIATED PRESS.\nVOLUME 13\nBISBEE, ARIZONA, SUNDAY MORNING, SEPTEMBER 25, 1910.\nNUMBER 118\nBISBEE\nI\nUc\nWTzaf s\n(By A. E. SUllwell).\nWhat Is \"Water\"? The answer of\nthe average man to-day would be:\n'\"The total Issue of stocks and bonds\nof the railroads, above their cost.\"\nWe will ,not deal In the large fig\nures of the total railroad Investment.\nWhen the Burlington (then the Kan\nsas City, St. Joseph's Council\nBluffs Read), reached Kansas Slty,\nit found a struggling town built on\nthe banks of the Missouri: Leaven\nworth was as large if not larger.\nThe Burlington bridged the Missouri\nand secured the subsidy of a large\nsection of land .for terminals, when\nthe lapd in Kansas City was not\nworth much. St. Joseph ,also gave\nit land.\nThe advent of this road secured\nfor Kansas City, its first real im\npetus, so that to-day it is one of the\nleading business cities in the United\nStates. Wide boulebards that would\ndo credit to Paris, beautify this great\ncity, cf wonderful growth. It ranks\nsecond ,in the country as a packing\ncenter and first as a market for long\nleaf pine. It is seventh as a bank\nclearance and Its many beautiful\nhomes illustrate that It is. cue of the\nmost attractive residence cities in\nthe new world.\nTho Burlington Road inaugurated\nKansas City's prosperity and many\nmillions of dollars were made through\nthe increased local values, originated\nby this railroad's\" advent. The Kan\nsas City land given to the Burlington,\nworth at the time comparatively lit\ntle Is probably valued today at $5,\n000,000 and doubtless earns Interest\non this sum. Is this \"Water\"?\nSimilarly; the corner of 9th and\nWalnut Streets, Kansas City was\nworth, (at tho t'me this other land\nwas given to the Burlington) prob\nably $2,000 per hundred feet; It Is\ndoubtless now worth and pays In\nterest on JC00.000. Is this \"Water\"?\nWhen the Burlington Road first\ncame to Kansas City, there were\nonly about 50,000,000 people in the\nUnited States, now there are 90,000.\n000 and the railroads are everywhere\nthe chief factors of this growth.\nSince tho Burlington created such\ntremendously increased land values\n(\"Water\"), In Kansas City, should\nnot their creative factor, the Burling\nton Road, be entitled to just a little\nIncreased value through bond or\nstock Issue \"Water\"?\nThe camel is about the only animal\nthat can long exist without water,\nand its home Is the desert. If we\nare to bo denied \"water\" (Increased\nvalue) in railroads or other business\nthere will bo a desert here, we are\nnot camels, and who wants to be a\nwww V W V 9-VW\nW .iitKfcrf--\n4 4\nELEQ. 7 RIQITY\nMEANS COMFORT AND SECURITY\nNo greasy Oil Lamps to clean, to fill or trim,, simply turn on current and flood\nyour house with Light. Electricity does not explode, smoke or eat up oxygen.\nJ\nIf located on our lines we will wire your house at cost, as follows\nHOUSE HAVING 3 GONNEQTING ROOMS 3\nThese\nn\nBISBEE IMPROVEMENT COMPANY\nloafer\ncamel? Even the camel will drink\nwater when he can get It\n\"Water\" Is as necessary In busi\nness affaire, as it is to sustain\nhuman life When a section of oar\nland lacks rain, plant life withers,\ncrops fail, and starvation faces man\nand beast; while the same region.\nscientifically Irrigated, as growing\";\nplants demand, will blossom like the\nrose.\nIt Is the same In the business\nworld. Take away the \"water\" (In\ncreased values or profit) and there\nIs a failure of good, healthy, busi\nness life; depression of business, peo\nple out of work, panic, and starva\ntion follow. Just as in a drought\nstricken section of the country.\n\"Water\" (Increased values) is the\nmain spring of Ambition; \"water\"\nhas conquered jthe world; without\nman's love for \"water\" there would\nbe no business life. People like to\nlook upon water; it is health giving.\nThey build their summer homes by\nthe Jake and the sea. It Is the same\nwith a man in business; he likes to\nsee \"water\" (Increased value). It\nwarms the cockles of his heart, ond\nnerves him for greater endeavor, and\nit brings health to the business\nworld.\n\"Watec.\" in business, is like tho\nbabbling brook; it refreshes the\ntraveler Journeying through the busi\nness world.\n\"Water\" (chances for gain), caus\ned our forefathers to cross the\nAlleghany Mountains to find cheap\nland and make a profit, pushing back\nthe borders of the West, fighting .the\nIndians, wresting the region from\nthem for \"water.\" Pioneers crossed\nthe JPIalns, abandoned homes and\ncivilization, .starved and died, to\npreach California, to find \"water\"\n(gold from tho mines).\nMen start manufactories, work out\npatents, build railroads, take ,life\nchances and risks, for \"water.\"\nMost people who do not care frr\n\"water\" do little upbuilding; tiey\nInvest in 3 per cent and 6, per cent\nloans, or Government bonds, and\nvegetate.\nThe love of \"water\" creates darinir\nspirits, who cross tho sea to pioneer\nin new countries, expand trade har\nness water power, erect great edi\nfices light cities, print papers, sail\nthe seas, tunnel the rivers, build tele\nphono lines, all for \"water\" (profits\nfrom their work.)\nThe nation which unwittingly dries\nup the natural business springs, stop3 i\nprogress, and wrests ambition from\nman.\nTo eliminate \"water\" (possible In\nmWWVWm W\" www\n\"yy\"-'\nprices include drop\nWith the above wiring you are equipped to use an electric iron or any other elec\ntrical appliance intended for domestic use, such as disc stove, toaster, curling iron,\nsewing machine motor, washing machine, etc., all of which lessen expense and'\nadd to the comfort of the. home.\ncreased profits from railroads) would\nstop their extension.\nOn western trails, in the olden\ndays, there were signs telling the\nnumber of miles to water, and these\nsigns often stimulated endeavors of\ntravelers,, almost dead with thirst,\nand enabled them to hold out until\nthe water was reached.\nIn place of Inaugurating measures\nwhich squeeze \"water\" out of the\nrailroads it would be far better for\nour nation to point the way where\ni \"water\" could be developed, through\njlhe bulIdlng ot ncw railroads, and\nother business enterprises.\nNoah understood water, floated a\nlimited company and survived; the\nrest, who took no stock in it were\ndrowned!\nYou will rind all great cities border\nlake, river or sea. And, too, you\nfind great business activity, labor em\nployed, and prosperity on every hand,\nwhen there is a chance for \"water\"\n(increased values) in business life.\nLook at the wonderful \"strides re\ncently taken by Argentine, Mexico,\nand Canada; note the millions and\nmillions that have gone into those\ncountries in the last thirty years.\nWhat has attracted this great capi\ntal? It is the chance for \"water\",\nwhich has caused this wonderful\nprosperity. Look at the market value\nof the Canadian Pacific and the\nMexidan Railways, brought about\nsimply because these nations do not\noject to Reasonable Profits (\"water\")\nIn the roads.\nAnd the United States had far bet\nter encourage man's natural and hon\nest love for \"water and the Nation's\nfuture will be as progressive as Its\npast. Let us not force our people to\nI become camels, and our laud a des-\nert!\nA traveler In one of the Southern\nstates, on a country road met an old\ndarkey, whose poor starved mule,\ndrew a heavy load; the wagon's\nshafts peculiarly extending two feet\nbeyond the mule's head. Tied be\ntween the protruding shafts was a\nflno bunch of green grass, but so far\nin advance of his nose that the sad\nmule could not reach the tempting\nTimothy. The traveler stopped the old\ndarkey and asked t \"Why the Dickens\nhave you put that grass where the\nmule can't reach it?\"\nThe old darkey laughed, and said:\n\"Boss, dat bunch o' grass am an In\ncentlf!\" \"A what?\" asked the traveler.\n\"An. -IncentiC' replied -the darkey.\n\"What is an incentif?\"\n\"Why, Boss, an incentif am some\nthin peekin' ahead, an mighty well\nworth walkln for. Boss; dat grass\nam an incentif to dat 'ere mule; it\nlooks mighty good to hiin. like as\nef he walk far enough he gits it; but\nef I glf it to 'im now, he'd forglt\n6\ncord, sockets and lamps and fees of city inspector but do not include wall switches or\nTRACTION MEN\nEXPECT GREAT\nREVIVAL SOON\nOne Item In Prosperity of the\nCountry Which Means Big\nDemand for Copper and\nCopper Wire\n(By Geo. L. Walker)\nA matter worthy of note is tho\nfact that the earnings of traction\ncompanies were more nearly main\ntained throuhout the panic period\nthan those of any group of steam\nrailroads or manufacturing enter\nprises. This means that new issues\n1 of traction bonds and stocks will\nbe among tha first securities to find\na market when financial confidence\nbegins to return and a considerable\nportion of such ne-v money will be\nused for the piirchnsa of copper\n(wire, brass car fittings, etc. It Is\nnow very evident that copper will\nbe one of the first commodities to\nfeel the effect cf reviving business\nconditions.\nTiie president of a 'large copper\nproducing company, who is in a pos\nition to Judge the situation accu\nrately, says: \"I do not believe there\nwill be another month like August\nthis year. The very heavy increase\nIn productioi, represented a cleanlng-\nup by the refineries of the July\naccumulation of cathodes, and there\nfore reflected more than the actual\nvolume of new copper coming from\ntho mines. The production will be\nmuch smaller during the remaining\nmonths of the year and consumption\nshould be maintained resulting in\nit and plum sudden stop walkln'! I\nknows dat mule. Boss!\"\nIt is the same In business life; the\nhope of \"water\" ahead is what keeps\nmen walking and working, it Is In\ncentive.\nThe darkey's philosophy applies to\nmen as well as to the mule.\nThe recent\" failure of railroad ef\nforts to raise traffic rates, in spite of\nthe fact that they are compelled to\npay higher prices for material and\nj labor, Jias removed any possible In\ncentive for capital to invest in rail\njroad securities. Unless this Incentive\nis re-established, want and financial\nunrest must continue.\n\na steadily decreasing surplus, which\nwill be shown by the Producers\" as-\nsoclatlon and foreign visible supply\nfigures.\"\nFurther improvement in tha\ntlstlcal posIUon of the mtal cannot have been pretty well discounted at\nfall to stimulate heavier buying by ready y the extreme decline in\nconsuming interests, both here and prices. It is quite probable that there\nabroad. Consumers are ca.Tylng no\nstocks of coper at present; but will\nfill their bins when thoy feel sure\nthe time has come for an advance in\nprices. This will tend to clean up\nV..-.,i.. t,..i.i k oiiin.-\n,i nwi,rin,. rJMn\"iM\n\nhi.:: utn f,rely lead tu a considerable\nadvance In prices.\nI am (satisfied that consumntlon is\nnow exceeding production, and that bave tt \"H bearing on security val\nthis has been the condition for sev- ues.\neral months past. The curtailment If the supremo court decides that\nof production by a number of lead- the Standard Oil and Tobacco com\ning producers was not absolutely panies are not punishable as trusts\nessential to tho stability of the In-1 under the Sherman law, negotia\ndustry. but It will greatly benefit pro- tlons for the consolidation ot the\nducers by hastening the recovery several large copper producing com\nfroin unsatisfactory statistical condl-' panies of the world will bo taken up\ntlons. Within six months at the long- J promptly and carried through a suc\nest the metal situation should be cessful Issue. If $hls \"is done it\nall right again and prices should cannot fall to encourage heavy spec\nbe showing advancing tendency even ulatlon in copper ming stocks,\nwith all the mines producing to t which will bring about a much\ntheir full li.m.IK' Vnthlnn hilt h'llpr I'lUlPS of nrlceS.\ngeneral business calamity and panic\ncan prevent the metal from advanc-\nl nrn,I....U in this nrlr-n\n.iuuai'j j........\nWhen stocks pet in a position\nwhen; they refuse to decline on bad\nnews It ts usually safe to buy and j\nhold them for a big advance. Thou-\nsands of beer traders were over- j\nJoyed last Monday evening when they,\nrevelved news of the democratic\nlandslide in Maine. They confident\nly expected a five' or 10 point break\nIn prices the next morning. After\nthe opening Tuesday a few of them\nsold more stocks, and the rest\nwaited for the public to sell. The\nmnrVot was tut badlv oversold,\never, that it refused to decline, andjof prosperity to the latter is depend- at high prices as we ever have in\nprices rallied. Jent upon more favorable political the past.\nWhile this refers in a general way developments the granting of privil-1 Sentiment continues generally bear,\nto the railroad and industrial stocks, ege to the railroad to advance freight Ish on the metal situation, and al\nthere being at present practically no J rates, a gradual reversal of tho J most everybody who is Inclined to\ntrading activity in coppers. It re-.foreign trade situation and the res-J buy copper stocks is being advised\nfleets faithfully the whole spcculat- toration of financial and buisness con\nIve situation. The coppers had their .fidence in the country. The copper\ndecline first, discounting the de- mines, however, are not depend\npression in the metal market early ent entirely upon Improvement In\nthis year. Since then the prices the domestic business and financial\nof these stocks have remained about conditions, as they find a market for\nstationary, awaiting a possible break a large portion of their product\nin the railroad and industrial shares, abroad, where trade conditions ap-\nThe metal situation has improved pear to be steadily growing better,\nsufficiently to warrant a considerable j In this country and all over tho\nadvance In the coppers; but traders, world, manufacturing and transpor\nhave refrained Trom buying heavily tation companies are endeavoring in\nspeculative developments In other dl- every way possible to work out new\nrections might cause the coppers to methods of economy. They cannot\nsell somewhat lower than they have reduce wages, and the one big field\nso far. The action of stocks this of possibilities is that of power. Tho\nweek, following the Maine lection,\nhas tended to, confirm the opinion\neld by a few Qood Judgos, that\nwe have been in a bull market ever\nOUTLETS\n6\nWe have a full line of electrical appliances and shall be pleased to\nHot Point Electric Irons at $4.50\nPut out on trial to responsible people.\n'since tho bar break which occurred\nin July.\nThere are still a good many un\nfavorable factors hanging over the\nsta-jniarket and although they probably\nmaY not De any conswerame aa-\nvance, or any great increase in actlv-\nlty. untN these\" factors havo been\neliminated. The November elec-\ntlons, tho settlement of the railroad\nfreleht-rate Increase Question, the\nfinal hearings before tho supreme\nl m it -.f\ncourc ana me am me aecisions o:\n'that Dody oa ,nt-' Tobacco and Scud-\nrd Oil cases, are matters which\nI if the railroads of this country\nare permitted to increase freight\nI t,o. rontii.Dta1 ItlUatlOn tQCn Was lDUCIl 3S it IS BOW.\n(Alva txa lucj mi.,.\nwm have the effect of re-establishing\ninvestment confidence In railroad\nsecurities, will make a market lor\nbonds and permit a resumption ot\nrailroad construction and equipment.\nThis will stimulate general business\ntremendously and greatly increase\nthe domestic demand for- copper,\nsteel and other commodities, hasten\ning the return of prosperity and In\nriuatrlal nracxess.\nOn the whole, the coppers arc\nnot In as bad a nositlon as the rail-\n\nhow-irnads and Industrials. The return\nonly cheaper power available for\ngeneral purposes than that produced\nby steam Is hydro-electric power,\nThere Is a great deal of develop-\n$9.00\n11.00\n13.00\n15.00\n4\nment in this line all OTer the world,\nand ft promises to become increas\ningly popular. The generation cf\npower from waterfalls, and Its dis\ntribution electrically to railways\nlighting plants and facorles is large\nly responsible for the present steady\ngrowth of copper consumption.\nThe substitution of electric for\nsteam locomotives on railroad Is\nproving so successful that all ot\nthe companies which have undertaken\nIt are now extending, or planning to\nextend, this form of equipment No\na llnnn A li ItTn ln nlflO.\nwu,, u.t u. m.\ntriclty has returned to steam power.\nunuouoieaiy me popularity ui cict;\ntrlc traction will continue to grow,\nuntil within a few years the work\nof electrifying all of the principal\ntrunk lines between the lar9 cities\nof the northeastern and central por\ntions of the United States will be\nundertaken. When this is done It\nwill so increase the demand for cop\nper that, even should the produc\ntion of all the new mines come up\nto the most sanguine expectations\nof their promters and stockholders\nthey will be unable to supply the\nworld's requirements.\nIn 1903, when copper was selling\nunder 13 cents, I predicted that It\nwould advance to 15 cents. Tho slt-\nj and I was charged with being over\nsanguine, anu naving me ODjecc in\nview of booming copper stocks. The\nprice of copper did not stop advanc\ning, however, until it reached 26\nceuts, notwithstanding that produc\ntion increased meanwhile between\n30 and 40 per cent. I am Just as\nconfident now that the developments\nof the coming five or six years will\nagain cause copper to advance to\n\nan aDnormauy nign price, anu inai\nwe shall witness as eager and en-\nthusiastic buying of copper stocks\nto wait for a still lower level of\nprices. Conservatism Is popular just\nnow but the propertlme to be con\nservative is when bullish specula\ntion is rampant and when stocks\nare high. I am satisfied that the\ncoppers are In a strong position\ntechnically, notwithstanding the pres\nent relatively unsatisfactory earn\nings, due to the low price of the\nimetal. The situation It already Im\nproving and within a few months\nthe outlook will be very much bright\ner than it is now. I would buy\ncopper stocks at current prices, and\nadd to my holdings every time tho\nmarket shows signs of weakness. All\nof the good coppers are selling for\nmuch less than they are actually\nworth.\nshades\nshow them.\nt\n\n'A\n\nr tf\nJ4-\n4\n4\nTELEPHONE NO. 197\nN","height":"26456","width":"21688"}}
